passages.text: Infrastructure Software Elastic! Raise PT to $125

Following strong infra prints from MDB and SNOW, ESTC posted a top-tier beat of 5% over guidance. However, the updated FY26 rev guide implies just 13-14% growth (vs F1Q's 20%), signaling continued caution. Recent sales team changes appear to be improving execution, but ESTC's track record remains uneven and growth still lags peers. While we credit the strength this Q, we favor faster-growing pure-play observability (DDOG, DT) and security (CRWD, PANW) names.

**What we liked: 1) F1Q results. F1Q rev beat the midpoint of guidance by $18M (record-sized beat) and grew 20% y/y vs Street** **ests at 14%. Cloud rev accelerated to 24% vs 23% last quarter and vs Street at 21%. Opm was 16% vs Street ests at 12%. 2) Leading indicators. Mgmt will begin regularly disclosing sales-led subscription rev (subscription rev excluding monthly cloud) and cRPO as the most relevant leading indicators for the business Subscription rev less monthly cloud was $339M and grew 20% y/y in CC, while 12-month cRPO was $956M and grew 17% in CC. 3) Security outperformance. Security was a clear focus in F1Q, with the term mentioned 31 times on the call vs. 14-22 in the prior 4 quarters. One-third of new and expansion deals in security came from displacing incumbents (mostly in SIEM with Splunk and QRadar), underscoring competitive wins. 4) Gen AI attach rates. ESTC ended F1Q with 2,200 customers using Elastic Cloud for Gen AI use cases, with >330 of those being >$100K ACV customers. The company also added more >$1M ACV customers with GenAI use cases than in the prior two quarters combined.

**What we're watching: 1) FY26 outlook. ESTC raised its guide by $22M at the midpoint, implying** 13-14% y/y growth vs prior guidance of 12%. The guide assumes some degree of improvement to the macro headwinds that were embedded in the initial outlook, although we believe there is a fair amount of conservatism left in the guide (13-14% implied growth vs F1Q's 20% and cRPO growth of 18%). 2) Sales productivity progress. Sales execution was solid with signs of stabilization in the US Public Sector, and mgmt indicated that productivity is tracking in line with expectations. We will be monitoring the progress from the dedicated security sales and technical GenAI specialist teams as the company continues to invest in high-priority growth areas. 3) Price increases at the beginning of F1Q. ESTC raised prices across both cloud and self-managed offerings in May. Mgmt noted that while F1Q growth was primarily driven by consumption and strong execution, pricing provided an incremental lift to y/y growth rates (while q/q growth rates would be less impacted). Monthly and annual prices were raised by approx. 5%.

**Our view. ESTC continues to underperform its peers in observability and security at smaller scale,** and we believe there is room for improvement on the GTM side. However, we are constructive on the improving sales execution and accelerating growth. Maintain Buy, raise PT to $125 (implies 7x CY26E rev).

Elastic's enterprise software platform ingests and stores data from any source, and in any format, and performs search, analysis, and visualization on this data in milliseconds. Developers build on top of the Elastic Stack to apply the power of search to their data and solve business problems. Since founding in 2012, ESTC has built additional features that address a wide variety of use cases including app search, site search, enterprise search, logging, metrics, application performance monitoring, business analytics, and security analytics.

Our \(\) 125\(PT is derived via a discounted cash flow (CoE 10.4%; TG 5%). Key risks include competition, including open - source developments, and the technical nature of the products from a sales perspective.
Our \(\) 500\(price target equates to 21x EV/CY26E rev and is one of the most expensive in our coverage universe. Risks include competition, slower market growth, and delayed profitability.

Our DCF- based price target of \(\) 160\(implies a multiple of 13x our CY26 total revenue estimate. Risks include competitive inroads as monitoring workloads consolidate; choppiness in enterprise sales execution, given that the motion is relatively young, early renewals for certain contracts driving estimate volatility, and multiple compression across high growth.
Our \(\) 65\(PT is based on a DCF analysis. Key risks include greater competition in the core APM market and pricing pressure over the longer term.

Our \(\) 235\(price target is based on a DCF (WACC 10%; TG 5%), which assumes higher growth in the out years and accounts for stock based comp. Downside risks: product sales slow, lower industry growth, incumbent vendors re- engaging.
